1
00:00:44,700 --> 00:00:47,500
Tell your client that Reata is my property.

2
00:00:47,500 --> 00:00:49,700
And the name of Reata is my property.

3
00:00:50,100 --> 00:00:52,100
The Texas courts are fair.

4
00:00:52,500 --> 00:00:56,100
He is to cease using the name of my ranch
in his oil schemes.

5
00:00:56,300 --> 00:00:59,900
I won't have oil digging on Reata.
I won't stand for its name being used.

6
00:01:00,100 --> 00:01:01,300
Is that clear?

7
00:01:11,700 --> 00:01:13,700
[Dynamic instrumental music]

8
00:01:29,500 --> 00:01:30,300
Mom?

9
00:01:32,900 --> 00:01:33,900
<i>Mother?</i>

10
00:01:34,100 --> 00:01:36,100
[Mellow band music]

11
00:01:49,100 --> 00:01:51,900
They say Aunt Luz was really in love
with Jett Rink herself.

12
00:01:51,900 --> 00:01:54,300
Even if she was old enough
to be his mother.

13
00:01:54,500 --> 00:01:55,500
Now, Luz....

14
00:01:55,500 --> 00:01:57,500
She was a character.

15
00:01:57,900 --> 00:02:00,500
She was always trying to keep him
from getting married.

16
00:02:00,500 --> 00:02:02,500
He had to run off to marry you.

17
00:02:02,700 --> 00:02:03,900
What's that?

18
00:02:04,500 --> 00:02:05,700
Who said what?

19
00:02:06,300 --> 00:02:07,700
Somebody. I forget.

20
00:02:12,300 --> 00:02:14,300
You know what they say?

21
00:02:14,500 --> 00:02:18,100
That every girl in Texas was trying
to catch Papa.

22
00:02:19,100 --> 00:02:20,300
They said, quote:

23
00:02:20,500 --> 00:02:23,700
"There wasn't a prize bull like him
since Sam Houston got married."

24
00:02:24,700 --> 00:02:25,900
That's enough from her.

25
00:02:27,100 --> 00:02:31,300
I'm sure it's quite true, darling.
It took me two whole days to land him.

26
00:02:33,900 --> 00:02:37,500
Really? It all sounds so fascinating
and uncouth.

27
00:03:00,100 --> 00:03:01,300
Where are you going?

28
00:03:02,500 --> 00:03:04,900
Down the road to Smitty's for Coke.

29
00:03:05,100 --> 00:03:05,900
BICK: With who?

30
00:03:06,100 --> 00:03:07,100
Nobody.

31
00:03:08,100 --> 00:03:09,300
Stay at home.

32
00:03:13,900 --> 00:03:14,900
Hey, you!

33
00:03:19,900 --> 00:03:20,700
Hello, Papa.

34
00:03:22,300 --> 00:03:23,100
Hi.

35
00:03:23,900 --> 00:03:25,100
Where have you been?

36
00:03:25,100 --> 00:03:26,900
Down the road for a Coke.

37
00:03:27,300 --> 00:03:28,300
With who?

38
00:03:28,500 --> 00:03:29,300
Bob.

39
00:03:34,300 --> 00:03:36,500
BOB: Howdy, Mr. Benedict.
BICK: Hello, Bob.

40
00:03:39,100 --> 00:03:41,100
Well, good night, Mr. Benedict.

41
00:03:41,500 --> 00:03:43,100
Excuse me, Papa.

42
00:03:55,900 --> 00:03:58,100
JUDY: Look, Papa, are you busy now?

43
00:03:58,500 --> 00:04:00,700
Never too busy for you, young fellow.

44
00:04:01,700 --> 00:04:03,300
BICK: What's on your mind?

45
00:04:03,700 --> 00:04:05,900
Well, Daddy, it's like this.

46
00:04:06,300 --> 00:04:08,300
JORDAN: I am, Mama. I'm going to be.

47
00:04:08,900 --> 00:04:11,900
<i>I want to go to Harvard</i>
<i>and then to Columbia premed.</i>

48
00:04:13,700 --> 00:04:15,300
So you want to be a doctor?

49
00:04:16,100 --> 00:04:17,100
Yes.

50
00:04:20,300 --> 00:04:23,700
How about Reata, Jordy?
He's counting on you to take over.

51
00:04:25,500 --> 00:04:27,700
Yes, I know he is. I know it.

52
00:04:29,100 --> 00:04:32,100
But there are 50,000 guys who can do it
better than I can.

53
00:04:32,700 --> 00:04:35,500
I don't want to live my life
pushing cows around.

54
00:04:37,900 --> 00:04:40,100
I'd die for Papa if I had to.

55
00:04:40,700 --> 00:04:44,700
Your father doesn't want you to die
for him. He wants you to live for him.

56
00:04:44,900 --> 00:04:46,700
Talk to her, will you, Daddy?

57
00:04:47,900 --> 00:04:49,300
Reason with her.

58
00:04:51,100 --> 00:04:52,700
I don't want this pinned on me.

59
00:04:52,700 --> 00:04:54,500
I'll take all the blame.

60
00:04:54,700 --> 00:04:57,700
You just sort of soften the blow a little bit.

61
00:04:58,900 --> 00:05:00,500
I'll talk to him myself.

62
00:05:00,700 --> 00:05:03,100
You can persuade him, Mom.
I know you can.

63
00:05:03,700 --> 00:05:05,500
It's not gonna be easy, honey.

64
00:05:08,500 --> 00:05:10,500
Maybe I can catch her at a weak moment.

65
00:05:10,700 --> 00:05:13,500
You can do it, Daddy. I know you can.

66
00:05:18,700 --> 00:05:20,900
LESLIE: Darling, I've been thinking....

67
00:05:22,100 --> 00:05:23,100
Me, too.

68
00:05:26,300 --> 00:05:27,900
LESLIE: About the children.

69
00:05:29,300 --> 00:05:31,100
That's funny. Me, too.

70
00:05:36,300 --> 00:05:37,700
We must be getting old.

71
00:05:38,500 --> 00:05:39,900
LESLIE: Speak for yourself.

72
00:05:43,300 --> 00:05:47,300
<i>I wonder if we love them enough</i>
<i>to do what's really right for them.</i>

73
00:05:48,100 --> 00:05:49,500
Why, sure.

74
00:05:52,500 --> 00:05:53,700
I hope so.

75
00:05:55,700 --> 00:05:56,700
LESLIE: I mean...

76
00:05:58,100 --> 00:06:00,500
so we love them too much perhaps.

77
00:06:01,300 --> 00:06:04,900
<i>So much that we keep from doing</i>
<i>what's right for them.</i>

78
00:06:06,300 --> 00:06:07,300
Not me.

79
00:06:10,100 --> 00:06:12,100
You don't have to worry about me.

80
00:06:18,100 --> 00:06:19,500
It's always the mother.

81
00:06:21,700 --> 00:06:25,500
The theory is she doesn't want
her fledglings to leave her nest.

82
00:06:28,300 --> 00:06:32,100
Try their own wings. All that sort of stuff.

83
00:06:35,100 --> 00:06:36,300
You mean...

84
00:06:37,900 --> 00:06:40,300
you'd be perfectly willing to sacrifice?

85
00:06:42,100 --> 00:06:43,100
Yeah.

86
00:06:45,100 --> 00:06:47,700
I'd sacrifice for her. You know that.

87
00:07:07,900 --> 00:07:10,700
I'm not so sold on that...

88
00:07:12,500 --> 00:07:15,300
girl's school in Switzerland you're stuck on.

89
00:07:15,500 --> 00:07:17,500
Now, don't get your feathers up.

90
00:07:18,300 --> 00:07:20,500
Judy's not crazy about that school either.

91
00:07:20,700 --> 00:07:23,500
Of course she isn't.
That's exactly why she needs to go.

92
00:07:24,700 --> 00:07:26,300
I wouldn't push her.

93
00:07:29,500 --> 00:07:30,500
She...

94
00:07:31,900 --> 00:07:33,700
wants to go to Texas Tech.

95
00:07:33,900 --> 00:07:35,500
That's a man's school.

96
00:07:36,100 --> 00:07:37,500
Girls go, too.

97
00:07:38,300 --> 00:07:41,700
It's got the best animal husbandry course
in the country, she says.

98
00:07:47,900 --> 00:07:50,500
She wants to be a rancher,
like her old man.

99
00:07:51,700 --> 00:07:53,100
Like Bob Dace.

100
00:07:53,900 --> 00:07:58,300
She's just got her little schoolgirl crush
on that hulking Bob Dace.

101
00:07:59,300 --> 00:08:02,300
She's got her mind set on it.

102
00:08:03,100 --> 00:08:04,700
That's what she wants.

103
00:08:05,900 --> 00:08:08,300
And I, for one, am willing to sacrifice.

104
00:08:35,100 --> 00:08:36,500
What do you say?

105
00:08:41,500 --> 00:08:44,500
It seems we've hatched
an odd pair of fledglings.

106
00:08:49,900 --> 00:08:51,100
<i>Brace yourself.</i>

107
00:08:51,900 --> 00:08:53,900
<i>Jordy wants to be a doctor.</i>

108
00:08:56,700 --> 00:08:57,500
He wants what?

109
00:08:57,700 --> 00:08:59,900
LESLIE: He wants to be a doctor.
He's set on it.

110
00:08:59,900 --> 00:09:02,500
Over my dead body!
You know what he's supposed to do.

111
00:09:02,500 --> 00:09:03,700
LESLIE: Well, he's not.

112
00:09:04,700 --> 00:09:08,700
<i>He'd die for you, but he's not gonna</i>
<i>live his life for you. And he's right.</i>

113
00:09:09,100 --> 00:09:10,700
He'll do as we've all done.

114
00:09:12,700 --> 00:09:16,900
He wants to go to Harvard first,
then Columbia premed.

115
00:09:19,100 --> 00:09:21,300
You're pretty handy with those terms.

116
00:09:22,700 --> 00:09:25,100
I can see who's been cooking this thing up.

117
00:09:30,900 --> 00:09:32,100
Of course...

118
00:09:33,300 --> 00:09:35,900
this would mean a big sacrifice
on your part.

119
00:09:53,700 --> 00:09:56,100
BICK: No matter where he goes to school...

120
00:09:57,300 --> 00:09:59,900
he comes right back home and runs Reata.

121
00:10:06,500 --> 00:10:08,900
LESLIE: I guess you were right
about one thing.

122
00:10:11,500 --> 00:10:12,500
BICK: Me?

123
00:10:13,500 --> 00:10:14,700
LESLIE: On one thing.

124
00:10:16,900 --> 00:10:18,700
<i>We are getting old.</i>

125
00:10:19,900 --> 00:10:20,900
BICK: Who?

126
00:10:21,300 --> 00:10:22,500
LESLIE: We are, Jordan.

127
00:10:25,500 --> 00:10:27,500
<i>We are the older generation.</i>

128
00:10:29,500 --> 00:10:30,500
<i>Aren't we?</i>

129
00:10:31,500 --> 00:10:32,700
<i>Suddenly?</i>

130
00:10:40,500 --> 00:10:41,900
BICK: I guess so.

131
00:10:54,900 --> 00:10:57,700
"...unless oil or gas shall have been struck
at a lesser depth."

132
00:10:57,900 --> 00:11:00,100
JETT: Is that about Vashti Hake's ranch?

133
00:11:02,300 --> 00:11:02,900
Yes.

134
00:11:04,900 --> 00:11:05,900
Good.

135
00:11:06,900 --> 00:11:07,900
How about Reata?

136
00:11:08,700 --> 00:11:11,900
No. That Benedict is a hard guy to crack.

137
00:11:19,300 --> 00:11:21,500
Let's just keep punching, boys.

138
00:11:21,700 --> 00:11:24,500
[lndustrious instrumental music]

139
00:11:54,700 --> 00:11:55,700
BAWLEY: Hospital!

140
00:11:56,100 --> 00:11:57,700
<i>What's he covering up now?</i>

141
00:11:58,300 --> 00:12:01,500
He'll overstep the mark one of these days.

142
00:12:01,700 --> 00:12:02,900
Give him enough rope.

143
00:12:03,900 --> 00:12:06,300
Give him enough rope, and he'll hang you.

144
00:12:06,500 --> 00:12:07,500
[Phone rings]

145
00:12:08,100 --> 00:12:09,100
I'll get it.

146
00:12:13,300 --> 00:12:14,500
Hello.

147
00:12:17,700 --> 00:12:19,500
No, this is her daughter.

148
00:12:24,500 --> 00:12:26,900
You'll have to find out for yourself.

149
00:12:27,900 --> 00:12:29,700
Take your social life on the other phone.

150
00:12:29,700 --> 00:12:30,700
LUZ II: It's for you.

151
00:12:30,900 --> 00:12:32,300
I think he's nice.

152
00:12:32,500 --> 00:12:34,100
BICK: Who's nice?
LUZ II: Jett Rink.

153
00:12:36,700 --> 00:12:38,100
I don't want to talk to him.

154
00:12:38,100 --> 00:12:39,500
What do I tell him?

155
00:12:40,100 --> 00:12:42,700
Let me talk. I'll tell him.

156
00:12:43,100 --> 00:12:44,500
I'll talk to him.

157
00:12:50,900 --> 00:12:53,300
You've heard from me before on this, Jett.

158
00:12:53,700 --> 00:12:56,100
Judge Whiteside told you, and I told you.

159
00:12:56,100 --> 00:13:00,100
This is a cattle ranch, not an oil field.
That's the way it's gonna stay.

160
00:13:02,900 --> 00:13:05,900
BAWLEY: That's the most expensive
phone call you ever made, Bick.

161
00:13:05,900 --> 00:13:08,900
It'll cost you a billion dollars a year
for the next 50 years.

162
00:13:08,900 --> 00:13:13,300
Couldn't we have just one little, itty-bitty
oil well, so I can get a private phone?

163
00:13:20,100 --> 00:13:22,100
[Clock chimes]

164
00:13:26,100 --> 00:13:28,100
[Romantic jazz music]

165
00:13:29,700 --> 00:13:32,300
REPORTER: [Over radio]
<i>After reporting to the President...</i>

166
00:13:32,300 --> 00:13:34,100
<i>the Naval Secretary told the press...</i>

167
00:13:34,100 --> 00:13:38,100
<i>that the battleship Arizona</i>
<i>and five other warships were lost...</i>

168
00:13:38,100 --> 00:13:42,700
<i>in the Japanese air raid</i>
<i>on Pearl Harbor a fortnight ago.</i>

169
00:13:43,700 --> 00:13:45,700
<i>He reported that 91 officers...</i>

170
00:13:46,100 --> 00:13:50,100
<i>and 2,638 enlisted men were known dead.</i>

171
00:13:56,300 --> 00:13:59,100
That only makes me realize I'm losing you.

172
00:14:17,100 --> 00:14:19,100
[Seductive jazz music]

173
00:14:39,900 --> 00:14:42,900
[Singing Christmas carol]

174
00:15:20,300 --> 00:15:21,700
Here they are.

175
00:15:24,500 --> 00:15:26,300
LUZ II: When did you two sneak in?

176
00:15:26,500 --> 00:15:28,100
The honeymooners!

177
00:15:34,100 --> 00:15:36,900
Judy, you're gonna get it.
You know Mom wanted a big wedding.

178
00:15:36,900 --> 00:15:38,700
That's not true, Luz.

179
00:15:40,900 --> 00:15:42,300
Not quite true.

180
00:16:06,500 --> 00:16:08,700
[Lighthearted instrumental music]

181
00:16:15,900 --> 00:16:17,900
POLO: We came for you to see ngel.

182
00:16:19,100 --> 00:16:21,500
<i>He's the first soldier from Reata.</i>

183
00:16:21,900 --> 00:16:24,500
BICK: Merry Christmas, Polo.
VASHTI: Merry Christmas.

184
00:16:29,100 --> 00:16:31,300
Isn't he a fine-looking soldier?

185
00:16:32,900 --> 00:16:34,300
Just a minute.

186
00:16:38,900 --> 00:16:40,900
Merry Christmas, ngel.

187
00:16:40,900 --> 00:16:41,900
NGEL: Thank you.

188
00:16:42,100 --> 00:16:45,900
Today the wish of all of us is
that the war ends quickly...

189
00:16:46,500 --> 00:16:49,700
and that you, ngel,
return safely to Reata...

190
00:16:51,300 --> 00:16:54,100
and to all of those who love you very much.

191
00:16:54,500 --> 00:16:56,500
BAWLEY: I'll drink a toast to that.

192
00:16:58,700 --> 00:17:00,500
Come on, now, and open it.

193
00:17:27,100 --> 00:17:29,700
-Hello, Dr. Guerra.
-Hello, Dr. Benedict.

194
00:17:30,300 --> 00:17:32,300
Just a little premature.

195
00:17:32,300 --> 00:17:33,500
I know, it takes time.

196
00:17:34,300 --> 00:17:36,100
<i>Jordan, this is Juana.</i>

197
00:17:37,300 --> 00:17:39,900
She's been training out at the hospital.

198
00:17:42,900 --> 00:17:45,500
It must be that darn north wind static.

199
00:17:47,300 --> 00:17:51,900
DR. GUERRA: Haven't you learned that
dry wind, friction, and a heavy carpet...

200
00:17:52,500 --> 00:17:55,900
are not the only means of creating
electricity between human beings.

201
00:18:03,900 --> 00:18:06,300
[Excited indistinct chatter]

202
00:18:10,300 --> 00:18:11,500
Thank you.

203
00:18:16,700 --> 00:18:19,700
Could you stay and give me the lowdown
on what it's like?

204
00:18:27,500 --> 00:18:29,900
-Very nice to meet you.
-Nice meeting you.

205
00:18:30,300 --> 00:18:32,100
-Goodbye.
<i>-Adis.</i>

206
00:18:34,500 --> 00:18:37,900
-Let's get some Christmas cheer.
-You talked me into it!

207
00:18:45,900 --> 00:18:49,300
Friends, we're gonna have
a mighty triumphant Christmas.

208
00:18:51,300 --> 00:18:54,300
I'm gonna drink a toast
to two young men of Reata.

209
00:18:56,100 --> 00:18:57,300
My two sons.

210
00:19:05,700 --> 00:19:07,500
Thank you, Mr. Benedict.

211
00:19:12,500 --> 00:19:15,100
Better take it easy on the bourbon, Dad.

212
00:19:15,900 --> 00:19:17,500
It's not good for you.

213
00:19:18,500 --> 00:19:19,900
I'm not kidding you.

214
00:19:25,700 --> 00:19:27,500
I hate to see ngel go.

215
00:19:27,900 --> 00:19:31,100
BICK: That boy is the best dang man
on the place.

216
00:19:36,500 --> 00:19:40,900
It's time for you to take your place here,
to produce beef for the war.

217
00:19:41,900 --> 00:19:45,100
They need doctors, Dad.
They need doctors in war, too.

218
00:19:46,900 --> 00:19:49,300
I want to finish medical school if I can.

219
00:19:50,100 --> 00:19:51,700
You are being bull-headed.

220
00:19:53,300 --> 00:19:55,900
I never would be any good
at running this place.

221
00:19:57,700 --> 00:19:59,900
Any man on Reata can do it better.

222
00:20:00,100 --> 00:20:01,700
You're the one.

223
00:20:02,900 --> 00:20:05,300
You're the one with a responsibility
to Reata.

224
00:20:05,500 --> 00:20:08,300
Your blood pressure is going up
just while we're talking here.

225
00:20:09,700 --> 00:20:12,100
Please, it isn't good for you. Just relax.

226
00:20:12,300 --> 00:20:14,100
Don't you get fresh with me.

227
00:20:20,500 --> 00:20:22,100
We're talking.

228
00:20:22,300 --> 00:20:23,700
Yes, I heard.

229
00:20:24,700 --> 00:20:29,100
It's Christmas morning. Isn't this
something you could discuss tomorrow?

230
00:20:30,500 --> 00:20:32,500
There's nothing to discuss.

231
00:20:32,700 --> 00:20:36,100
When I come home,
I'll work with Dr. Guerra in Vientecito.

232
00:20:38,900 --> 00:20:42,100
I love Texas as much as you do.
I want to work here.

233
00:20:43,100 --> 00:20:46,100
I just want to work in a different way,
that's all.

234
00:20:47,500 --> 00:20:48,700
LESLIE: Come on, Jordan.

235
00:20:50,700 --> 00:20:52,100
BICK: Work with Guerra!

236
00:21:04,100 --> 00:21:05,700
Here's to you, Mr. Benedict.

237
00:21:10,300 --> 00:21:12,300
You look beat, Mr. Benedict.

238
00:21:12,500 --> 00:21:13,500
Here's to you.

239
00:21:13,500 --> 00:21:15,100
It's pretty good stuff.

240
00:21:15,900 --> 00:21:17,700
Did you make that yourself?.

241
00:21:19,300 --> 00:21:21,100
Yes, I make it every year.

242
00:21:22,700 --> 00:21:24,700
It's my Christmas special.

243
00:21:25,100 --> 00:21:26,900
BOB: No, I mean the liquor.

244
00:21:27,300 --> 00:21:29,100
Did you make the liquor yourself?.

245
00:21:29,500 --> 00:21:33,300
If not, it's about the only thing
you don't produce on Reata yourself.

246
00:21:37,900 --> 00:21:39,500
Come here and sit down.

247
00:21:40,100 --> 00:21:42,100
I've got some serious talk
to make with you.

248
00:21:49,300 --> 00:21:52,700
I've been watching you pretty close
for a lot of years.

249
00:21:57,100 --> 00:21:58,700
You're a ranchman.

250
00:22:00,500 --> 00:22:02,100
And you're smart.

251
00:22:10,900 --> 00:22:13,500
You're wondering why I'm talking to you.

252
00:22:20,900 --> 00:22:22,100
Bob Dace...

253
00:22:23,300 --> 00:22:24,700
look me right in the eye.

254
00:22:28,300 --> 00:22:32,900
You could never be anything but a rancher,
could you?

255
00:22:33,100 --> 00:22:34,700
-No, sir.
-That's my boy.

256
00:22:34,900 --> 00:22:37,300
But somebody else thinks I could.

257
00:22:39,100 --> 00:22:40,100
Not my Judy.

258
00:22:40,100 --> 00:22:41,700
-No, sir, it's not Judy.
-Who?

259
00:22:42,900 --> 00:22:44,500
President Roosevelt.

260
00:22:47,300 --> 00:22:48,900
Listen to this:

261
00:22:53,100 --> 00:22:55,300
"To Robert Haskell Dace.

262
00:22:56,100 --> 00:23:00,100
"Greetings from the President
of the United States."

263
00:23:00,300 --> 00:23:01,500
Let me see that.

264
00:23:04,100 --> 00:23:08,100
"You are hereby notified to report
on December 28...

265
00:23:08,500 --> 00:23:10,300
"5:00 a.m. for induction."

266
00:23:16,100 --> 00:23:17,500
BICK: It don't matter.

267
00:23:18,900 --> 00:23:21,300
Your job won't let you leave this place.

268
00:23:21,500 --> 00:23:25,100
It'll make you stay right here.
This is just as important as carrying a gun.

269
00:23:25,100 --> 00:23:27,300
I appreciate your confidence, sir.

270
00:23:28,100 --> 00:23:31,500
But this is one thing
I'm not gonna try to get out of.

271
00:23:35,100 --> 00:23:37,300
Have it your way. You might as well...

272
00:23:37,900 --> 00:23:40,100
everybody else does around here.

273
00:23:42,500 --> 00:23:45,900
I'll show you my heart's in the right place.

274
00:23:46,700 --> 00:23:49,500
When you come back
after the war is over...

275
00:23:50,300 --> 00:23:51,700
the job's yours.

276
00:23:51,900 --> 00:23:53,700
It'll be waiting for you.

277
00:23:55,500 --> 00:23:57,100
I couldn't take it, sir.

278
00:23:57,100 --> 00:23:59,300
Papa, Bob and I have plans.

279
00:24:01,300 --> 00:24:03,500
We want a place, just our own.

280
00:24:06,500 --> 00:24:08,300
BICK: You crazy kids, you!

281
00:24:10,500 --> 00:24:13,700
Can you imagine you'll ever have
anything like this? Like Reata?

282
00:24:13,900 --> 00:24:16,500
Gosh, no, sir. We just want a little place.

283
00:24:16,700 --> 00:24:21,100
Just a little place that'll allow us time
for experimentation and progress.

284
00:24:21,100 --> 00:24:24,100
See, sir, big stuff is old stuff now.

285
00:24:24,500 --> 00:24:26,500
Big stuff is old stuff?.

286
00:24:26,500 --> 00:24:30,900
Bob didn't mean to upset you.
He just wants to be honest, that's all.

287
00:24:31,900 --> 00:24:35,500
We just want something little
that's our own. That's all.

288
00:24:36,500 --> 00:24:37,900
Just ours.

289
00:24:38,700 --> 00:24:40,300
You see, Dad?

290
00:24:41,700 --> 00:24:43,700
Yeah, honey, I see.

291
00:24:46,900 --> 00:24:48,500
See you, Daddy.

292
00:25:00,100 --> 00:25:02,700
BICK: Keeping it together all my life
for them!

293
00:25:03,300 --> 00:25:06,500
<i>I battled mesquite, dust, and the wind...</i>

294
00:25:07,100 --> 00:25:08,700
to keep it this big.

295
00:25:09,700 --> 00:25:10,900
<i>And for who?</i>

296
00:25:11,900 --> 00:25:15,100
<i>I might just as well give it back</i>
<i>to the dirty Comanches!</i>

297
00:25:15,500 --> 00:25:16,900
LUZ II: That's the Christmas spirit.

298
00:25:16,900 --> 00:25:19,300
Give it all back to the poor old lndians.

299
00:25:24,700 --> 00:25:27,700
LUZ II: Don't tell me, I know.
You're Jett Rink.

300
00:25:30,900 --> 00:25:32,100
You're Judy.

301
00:25:32,100 --> 00:25:33,500
LUZ II: No, I'm Luz.

302
00:25:37,700 --> 00:25:38,700
<i>That I am.</i>

303
00:25:38,700 --> 00:25:40,100
<i>Come on in.</i>

304
00:25:46,900 --> 00:25:48,900
LUZ II: Dad's over at the bar.

305
00:25:50,300 --> 00:25:53,100
Feel free, it's Christmas.
Everybody gets one.

306
00:25:55,500 --> 00:25:56,700
Christmas?

307
00:25:57,900 --> 00:26:01,500
I thought that was next week.
Somebody ought to have told me.

308
00:26:03,300 --> 00:26:06,100
Christmas greetings
from Mr. Jetexas himself.

309
00:26:19,300 --> 00:26:20,500
Sit down.

310
00:26:25,900 --> 00:26:29,500
I guess Christmas is as good a day as any
to talk business.

311
00:26:32,500 --> 00:26:33,700
Run along, Luz.

312
00:26:34,700 --> 00:26:36,900
<i>We've got business to talk about.</i>

313
00:26:36,900 --> 00:26:37,900
'Bye, now.

314
00:26:40,300 --> 00:26:41,700
'Bye, Mr. Rink.

315
00:26:43,500 --> 00:26:45,700
Everybody calls me Jett, honey.

316
00:26:52,300 --> 00:26:53,500
Bye-bye.

317
00:27:02,100 --> 00:27:03,700
What's on your mind?

318
00:27:03,700 --> 00:27:05,900
JETT: The country needs petroleum.

319
00:27:06,700 --> 00:27:08,700
I'm going to Washington, Bick.

320
00:27:09,300 --> 00:27:12,300
The reason I'm going
and the reason I'm here is oil.

321
00:27:14,300 --> 00:27:15,700
I figured.

322
00:27:17,100 --> 00:27:19,100
You want to talk a little business?

323
00:27:19,700 --> 00:27:20,900
I'm ready.

324
00:27:22,100 --> 00:27:25,300
It seems that every time we made a deal,
me and you...

325
00:27:28,700 --> 00:27:30,900
it just turned out pretty lucky...

326
00:27:32,300 --> 00:27:33,500
for somebody.

327
00:27:37,500 --> 00:27:39,500
[Exciting instrumental music]

328
00:28:07,700 --> 00:28:11,300
All this oil around here hasn't made
a lot of difference.

329
00:28:12,300 --> 00:28:15,300
We live pretty much like we always have
here in Reata.

330
00:28:16,300 --> 00:28:18,100
BAWLEY: Just like we Benedicts found it.

331
00:28:20,100 --> 00:28:24,100
The Lord was good to you, to set
the swimming pool in your own front yard.

332
00:28:27,100 --> 00:28:28,700
Hey, come on in.

333
00:28:29,700 --> 00:28:31,100
BICK: Not now, Luz.

334
00:28:36,100 --> 00:28:38,300
It's good for the young folks.

335
00:28:39,500 --> 00:28:42,300
We'd have made improvements
around here, oil or no oil.

336
00:28:43,100 --> 00:28:46,700
But that 27.5 percent tax exemption
on oil helped, didn't it?

337
00:28:49,100 --> 00:28:51,500
Bale, I'll tell you what old Pinky thinks.

338
00:28:51,500 --> 00:28:52,300
What?

339
00:28:52,300 --> 00:28:56,700
That oil tax exemption is the best thing
to hit Texas since we whooped Geronimo.

340
00:29:04,700 --> 00:29:07,700
One of the finest laws ever passed
in Washington.

341
00:29:08,700 --> 00:29:11,100
And all joking aside, Bick...

342
00:29:11,300 --> 00:29:14,300
we're not adverse to accepting
a share of the credit for it.

343
00:29:14,500 --> 00:29:15,700
Not at all.

344
00:29:16,100 --> 00:29:20,300
How about an exemption for depreciation
of first-class brains, Senator?

345
00:29:20,500 --> 00:29:22,100
WHITESIDE: Whose? Yours?

346
00:29:22,500 --> 00:29:26,900
My father's, for instance. He spent his life
saving other people's lives.

347
00:29:27,700 --> 00:29:30,100
How about some tax exemption there?

348
00:29:35,300 --> 00:29:38,700
Leslie has always been a real sharp talker,
ain't she?

349
00:29:39,100 --> 00:29:42,700
Fair enough, Judge. You've always been
smooth enough for two.

350
00:29:44,100 --> 00:29:47,700
PRIEST: "Do you take each other
for better or for worse...

351
00:29:48,900 --> 00:29:50,900
"for richer or for poorer...

352
00:29:51,700 --> 00:29:54,500
"in sickness and in health, until death?

353
00:29:58,500 --> 00:30:01,700
"Jordan Benedict, wilt thou take...

354
00:30:02,300 --> 00:30:04,300
"Juana Villalobos here present...

355
00:30:05,100 --> 00:30:09,500
"for your lawful wife, according to
the rite of our Holy Mother the Church?"

356
00:30:10,900 --> 00:30:11,900
I will.

357
00:30:13,100 --> 00:30:16,100
PRIEST: "Juana Villalobos, wilt thou take...

358
00:30:17,100 --> 00:30:19,300
"Jordan Benedict here present...

359
00:30:19,300 --> 00:30:23,900
"for your lawful husband, according to
the rite of our Holy Mother the Church?"

360
00:30:25,700 --> 00:30:26,700
I will.

361
00:30:27,700 --> 00:30:29,900
PRIEST: Join your hands and kneel down.

362
00:30:39,900 --> 00:30:42,900
[Lively band music]

363
00:31:03,500 --> 00:31:05,700
[Square-dancing music]

364
00:32:30,700 --> 00:32:32,300
What did they say?

365
00:32:37,900 --> 00:32:39,500
<i>Friends and neighbors...</i>

366
00:32:40,900 --> 00:32:42,700
<i>I want you all to meet my wife.</i>

367
00:32:44,500 --> 00:32:46,100
<i>Mrs. Jordan Benedict III.</i>

368
00:32:47,700 --> 00:32:48,900
Congratulations!

369
00:34:03,500 --> 00:34:06,100
He was the first Reata baby I ever saw.

370
00:34:07,900 --> 00:34:10,300
I remember it as if it were yesterday.

371
00:34:12,700 --> 00:34:14,100
He had a fever.

372
00:34:15,900 --> 00:34:18,900
I didn't think he was going
to live the day out.

373
00:34:27,100 --> 00:34:29,500
[Priest reciting funeral rites in Spanish]

374
00:34:59,300 --> 00:35:01,300
[Train whistle blows]

375
00:35:19,700 --> 00:35:24,500
On behalf of the U.S. Army, I am proud
to present to you the flag of our nation...

376
00:35:25,100 --> 00:35:27,700
which your son defended so gallantly.

377
00:35:38,700 --> 00:35:40,700
[Trumpet playing taps]

378
00:36:12,300 --> 00:36:13,300
[Gunshot]

379
00:36:14,300 --> 00:36:16,300
[Choir singing the National Anthem]

380
00:37:39,300 --> 00:37:41,700
LUZ II: Everyone in the world's
gonna be there.

381
00:37:42,700 --> 00:37:45,500
I'm gonna fly up to Dallas,
and I'm going to Neiman's.

382
00:37:45,900 --> 00:37:49,500
I'll buy myself
a starlight-white evening dress.

383
00:37:50,100 --> 00:37:53,100
Very plain and simple and deadly.

384
00:37:54,300 --> 00:37:56,300
Before you get so elaborate and simple...

385
00:37:56,300 --> 00:37:58,700
you'd better hear
what your father has to say.

386
00:37:58,900 --> 00:38:01,100
We're certainly going. I promised Jett.

387
00:38:02,300 --> 00:38:05,100
Jett! What are you talking about?

388
00:38:05,700 --> 00:38:10,100
He likes me. He likes my family, too.
He's always talking about you.

389
00:38:12,100 --> 00:38:13,900
My dear, darling Luz...

390
00:38:14,300 --> 00:38:18,300
if I didn't know you had a level Benedict
head on those immature shoulders...

391
00:38:18,300 --> 00:38:20,500
I'd prescribe a good spanking.

392
00:38:20,700 --> 00:38:23,700
He's dreamy. Ask the Snythe girls.

393
00:38:23,900 --> 00:38:25,100
<i>Ask anyone.</i>

394
00:38:25,300 --> 00:38:27,300
<i>He's just a rough diamond.</i>

395
00:38:27,300 --> 00:38:31,500
He's a rough rhinestone.
He's old enough to be your father.

396
00:38:33,100 --> 00:38:35,100
What are you six evil men up to now?

397
00:38:35,300 --> 00:38:37,700
BAWLEY: Honey, it's a coronation.

398
00:38:38,300 --> 00:38:40,500
<i>Jett plans to get himself crowned king.</i>

399
00:38:40,500 --> 00:38:42,900
You got to have $10 million
to be on the guest list.

400
00:38:43,100 --> 00:38:45,700
The most important people
in the country will be there.

401
00:38:45,700 --> 00:38:47,500
<i>Coast-to-coast broadcast.</i>

402
00:38:47,500 --> 00:38:49,500
Jett's gonna make a magnificent speech.

403
00:38:49,700 --> 00:38:50,500
I know.

404
00:38:51,500 --> 00:38:53,500
<i>I'm going to write it for him.</i>

405
00:38:53,500 --> 00:38:55,700
lt'll be heard across the nation
by everyone.

406
00:38:55,700 --> 00:38:58,500
Eliminating one. That's me.

407
00:39:00,300 --> 00:39:04,700
If you people stay away, Leslie, you'll be
the only folks in Texas who ain't there.

408
00:39:04,700 --> 00:39:06,700
You'll be roped in with the herd.

409
00:39:06,700 --> 00:39:10,900
You'll be putting on your pink shoes and
dancing to Jett's fiddles like the rest of us.

410
00:39:10,900 --> 00:39:13,100
If we go then we'll do it right.

411
00:39:13,100 --> 00:39:17,700
We're oil rich, like the rest of them.
We'll go like the rest of them! Only better.

412
00:39:17,900 --> 00:39:19,500
Now you're talking like my father.

413
00:39:19,700 --> 00:39:21,300
BICK: The old Benedict spirit.

414
00:39:21,300 --> 00:39:23,500
You set up one of your great weekends.

415
00:39:23,500 --> 00:39:25,700
lnvite everybody.
We'll take them all with us.

416
00:39:25,700 --> 00:39:28,900
We'll show that so-and-so
who's top people around here.

417
00:39:29,100 --> 00:39:31,300
<i>I'll even buy the four-engine Douglas.</i>

418
00:39:31,500 --> 00:39:33,700
Fly in some orchids from Hawaii.

419
00:39:35,300 --> 00:39:38,900
We'll fly in low and shake the tiles
off that hotel roof.

420
00:39:38,900 --> 00:39:40,100
[Bick mimicking a plane engine]

421
00:39:40,300 --> 00:39:42,300
[Plane engine roaring]

422
00:40:37,300 --> 00:40:38,900
There's Lola Lane!

423
00:40:38,900 --> 00:40:41,100
I bet even Hollywood isn't this exciting.

424
00:40:41,300 --> 00:40:43,700
-Isn't this something?
-It's perfectly fabulous!

425
00:40:43,700 --> 00:40:46,100
Jett always tries to do things
in a bigger way...

426
00:40:46,100 --> 00:40:48,300
and spend more money than anybody else.

427
00:40:48,300 --> 00:40:49,700
Really? What does he do?

428
00:40:50,300 --> 00:40:52,900
BAWLEY: To some folks, he's
a no-good wildcatting so-and-so.

429
00:40:55,100 --> 00:40:57,100
[Drum roll of marching band]

430
00:41:03,100 --> 00:41:05,100
[Marching band plays lively song]

431
00:41:11,300 --> 00:41:12,300
There he is.

432
00:41:12,900 --> 00:41:14,300
[Crowd cheering]

433
00:41:18,900 --> 00:41:20,700
There's the emperor himself.

434
00:41:28,300 --> 00:41:31,700
Isn't this terrific?
Look at Luz, she's queen of the parade.

435
00:41:32,300 --> 00:41:33,900
You didn't tell me.

436
00:41:38,100 --> 00:41:40,100
Did you know about this, Leslie?

437
00:41:41,900 --> 00:41:42,900
No, I didn't.

438
00:41:49,100 --> 00:41:52,500
My daughter, queen of Jett Rink Day!
What is this?

439
00:41:53,900 --> 00:41:55,500
I don't know, Jordan.

440
00:41:56,900 --> 00:41:59,900
BICK: She's done things before
I haven't agreed with, but this....

441
00:41:59,900 --> 00:42:01,700
She's never been sneaky.

442
00:42:01,900 --> 00:42:04,900
It's not exactly sneaky,
appearing in a parade.

443
00:42:04,900 --> 00:42:06,500
BICK: Don't try to be funny.

444
00:42:06,900 --> 00:42:09,500
LESLIE: I'm not.
I'm just as upset as you are.

445
00:42:10,500 --> 00:42:14,100
But Luz is intelligent enough
not to be imposed on by him or anyone.

446
00:42:14,300 --> 00:42:15,700
Give me the desk.

447
00:42:16,700 --> 00:42:17,700
It's Bick Benedict.

448
00:42:17,900 --> 00:42:20,100
Did my daughter Luz Benedict come in yet?

449
00:42:20,900 --> 00:42:23,700
Get this. As soon as she comes in,
have her call me.

450
00:42:27,300 --> 00:42:29,300
[Languid instrumental music]

451
00:43:00,500 --> 00:43:02,500
You know what I think I'll do?

452
00:43:04,900 --> 00:43:07,300
I'm going to keep it just like this.

453
00:43:09,700 --> 00:43:12,500
I'll keep all those people, send them home.

454
00:43:15,300 --> 00:43:17,300
I'm not even gonna open up this place.

455
00:43:20,300 --> 00:43:23,500
Some girls might like a hotel
all to themselves.

456
00:43:24,500 --> 00:43:27,300
Me, I like company, Jett.
I like lots of people.

457
00:43:29,900 --> 00:43:31,100
All right.

458
00:43:32,300 --> 00:43:35,900
You want lots of people?
I don't see any problem there.

459
00:43:40,500 --> 00:43:44,500
If there's anything you want,
just say it, and you've got it.

460
00:43:48,300 --> 00:43:50,300
All right, I'd like a Coke.

461
00:43:54,300 --> 00:43:57,100
No, that's impossible.
That's just impossible.

462
00:43:58,100 --> 00:44:01,700
You know as well as I do, Cokes are taboo.
All soft drinks.

463
00:44:04,500 --> 00:44:06,100
You make the rules.

464
00:44:11,100 --> 00:44:13,700
You like things your own way, don't you?

465
00:44:14,700 --> 00:44:16,700
Let me ask you something.

466
00:44:17,700 --> 00:44:22,100
Do you like things your way?
Not many people have things their way.

467
00:44:23,300 --> 00:44:25,900
No, I don't get them my way very often.

468
00:44:29,900 --> 00:44:32,700
And you won't either,
until you get married...

469
00:44:35,300 --> 00:44:38,100
and get your man
to give you what you want.

470
00:44:38,100 --> 00:44:39,100
So?

471
00:44:40,300 --> 00:44:43,500
So if I was you,
I'd start thinking about getting married.

472
00:44:44,900 --> 00:44:46,700
You know, that's an idea.

473
00:44:53,700 --> 00:44:56,500
You looked like a queen
in that parade today.

474
00:44:57,500 --> 00:44:58,900
That was my job.

475
00:45:09,500 --> 00:45:11,100
It's just what you are.

476
00:45:11,900 --> 00:45:13,700
Luz Benedict ll.

477
00:45:16,300 --> 00:45:20,100
You could be the head lady
of this part of the whole country...

478
00:45:21,100 --> 00:45:24,100
if you wanted to.
If you married the right man.

479
00:45:25,700 --> 00:45:27,100
That's a sweet idea.

480
00:45:29,500 --> 00:45:31,900
Why don't I just announce it tonight...

481
00:45:32,300 --> 00:45:35,300
with all them thousands
of people listening?

482
00:45:37,700 --> 00:45:39,100
The whole of Texas.

483
00:45:41,300 --> 00:45:43,700
Wouldn't that blow the roof off?.

484
00:45:48,100 --> 00:45:50,100
Jett, tell me something.

485
00:45:54,300 --> 00:45:55,700
Is this a proposal?

486
00:45:55,900 --> 00:45:57,300
Does it sound like one?

487
00:46:00,100 --> 00:46:02,300
After a fashion, but not quite.

488
00:46:06,300 --> 00:46:09,100
You want me to say something
you can laugh at?

489
00:46:11,500 --> 00:46:12,500
No.

490
00:46:15,500 --> 00:46:18,100
I just think you're a wonderful girl.

491
00:46:19,500 --> 00:46:21,900
And I do think you're beautiful.

492
00:46:25,700 --> 00:46:29,500
You're fascinating to me.
I've always been looking for...

493
00:46:30,300 --> 00:46:31,700
a girl like you.

494
00:46:43,300 --> 00:46:46,100
Sure would blow the roof off, wouldn't it?

495
00:46:50,300 --> 00:46:52,500
You've got a long way to go tonight.

496
00:46:57,700 --> 00:47:00,300
I'm very flattered. Any girl would be.

497
00:47:06,100 --> 00:47:07,900
You be a good boy now.

498
00:47:09,500 --> 00:47:10,900
I'll see you later.

499
00:48:05,300 --> 00:48:07,300
[Wind howling]

500
00:48:12,900 --> 00:48:15,700
CLERK: I hope this storm
doesn't louse up your party.

501
00:48:15,700 --> 00:48:19,500
JETT: A slip-up, boy. I just forgot
to order the right kind of weather!

502
00:48:20,100 --> 00:48:21,300
CLERK: I heard a twister hit Waco.

503
00:48:34,700 --> 00:48:35,900
[Guard speaks Spanish]

504
00:48:35,900 --> 00:48:37,900
[Juana responds in Spanish]

505
00:48:38,900 --> 00:48:41,500
What's wrong with you?
Can't you talk United States?

506
00:48:41,700 --> 00:48:43,100
You're talking to my wife.

507
00:48:43,700 --> 00:48:46,900
I'm Jordan Benedict,
if that means anything to you.

508
00:48:47,300 --> 00:48:49,100
I'm just following orders.

509
00:48:49,500 --> 00:48:52,500
Mr. Rink said he'd have my neck
if I let any of the wrong people in.

510
00:49:00,500 --> 00:49:03,700
You Benedicts are all close together.
They've got the Coronado suite.

511
00:49:03,900 --> 00:49:05,300
You're in the Filando suite.

512
00:49:05,300 --> 00:49:08,100
I'm a mess. I must go to the beauty parlor.

513
00:49:08,100 --> 00:49:10,100
Hurry before they close.

514
00:49:10,100 --> 00:49:13,100
ANNOUNCER: [Over radio]
<i>Grand opening of the Jett Rink Airport...</i>

515
00:49:13,100 --> 00:49:14,300
<i>and Emperador Hotel...</i>

516
00:49:14,700 --> 00:49:18,700
<i>is the latest milestone in the dramatic</i>
<i>life of this virile son of Texas.</i>

517
00:49:21,300 --> 00:49:22,500
Howdy, everybody!

518
00:49:25,700 --> 00:49:28,300
ADARENE: It's time you arrived.
VASHTI: Where are the boys?

519
00:49:28,500 --> 00:49:29,900
<i>Where's Pinky, the old bat?</i>

520
00:49:30,700 --> 00:49:32,500
Filando suite for Mr. Benedict, please.

521
00:49:33,500 --> 00:49:34,700
HAIRDRESSER:
<i>Beauty salon.</i>

522
00:49:34,700 --> 00:49:36,100
Can you take me?

523
00:49:37,100 --> 00:49:39,100
HAIRDRESSER:
<i>Yes, if you can come right along.</i>

524
00:49:39,100 --> 00:49:41,100
Thank goodness. I'll be right in.

525
00:49:41,100 --> 00:49:43,300
<i>HAIRDRESSER: Who's calling?</i>
<i>JUANA: Mrs. Benedict.</i>

526
00:49:43,700 --> 00:49:45,700
HAlRDRESSER:
<i>Come on along, Mrs. Benedict.</i>

527
00:49:45,700 --> 00:49:46,700
Thank you.

528
00:49:49,100 --> 00:49:51,500
Keep everybody freshened up, will you?
We'll be quick.

529
00:49:51,700 --> 00:49:54,900
We're anxious to see old Jett come out
in that suit.

530
00:49:57,900 --> 00:50:01,300
Why couldn't they ride with us
like other people's kids do?

531
00:50:01,500 --> 00:50:04,900
<i>Luz had to fly her own plane</i>
<i>and Jordy and Juana had to drive.</i>

532
00:50:27,500 --> 00:50:28,900
JUANA: Is anybody here?

533
00:50:33,100 --> 00:50:34,700
We're all booked up.

534
00:50:34,700 --> 00:50:37,100
JUANA: I just called. I'm Mrs. Benedict.

535
00:50:38,900 --> 00:50:40,900
I'm sorry, but we're busy.

536
00:50:41,900 --> 00:50:43,700
I'll wait a little.

537
00:50:51,100 --> 00:50:53,900
LESLIE: They're driving. It takes time.

538
00:50:54,100 --> 00:50:55,900
BICK: I know it takes time.

539
00:50:56,900 --> 00:50:58,900
<i>I made the trip myself 400 times.</i>

540
00:51:01,900 --> 00:51:04,100
But don't worry about the children.

541
00:51:04,100 --> 00:51:06,900
Their behavior is odd,
but their manners are beautiful.

542
00:51:07,100 --> 00:51:08,500
LESLIE: Listen here, boy!

543
00:51:08,500 --> 00:51:10,500
<i>I've taken enough from you!</i>

544
00:51:10,700 --> 00:51:12,500
<i>I didn't want to come here!</i>

545
00:51:12,500 --> 00:51:15,300
<i>I wouldn't be here unless you let them</i>
<i>bully you into it.</i>

546
00:51:15,300 --> 00:51:17,700
<i>Now, for heaven's sake,</i>
<i>let's make the best of it.</i>

547
00:51:17,900 --> 00:51:21,900
Cool down, go on with your shaving, finish
dressing, and I'll go downstairs with you!

548
00:51:22,100 --> 00:51:24,100
Otherwise, you can go alone!

549
00:51:25,500 --> 00:51:26,700
You know, honey...

550
00:51:28,100 --> 00:51:30,300
you're awful cute when you get riled.

551
00:51:38,100 --> 00:51:41,500
Hurry on in there.
Your ma and pa are sure having a battle.

552
00:51:45,500 --> 00:51:46,700
Hello, honey.

553
00:51:46,700 --> 00:51:47,900
Where have you been?

554
00:51:48,100 --> 00:51:49,900
We got tied up in traffic.

555
00:51:49,900 --> 00:51:50,900
LESLIE: Where's Juana?

556
00:51:51,100 --> 00:51:53,300
She's in the beauty parlor.

557
00:51:54,500 --> 00:51:56,700
LESLIE: Hello, sweetheart.

558
00:51:57,500 --> 00:51:59,900
JORDAN: He's all right.
He just didn't get his nap.

559
00:51:59,900 --> 00:52:00,900
[Baby crying]

560
00:52:01,500 --> 00:52:03,500
BOB: How's my child?

561
00:52:04,500 --> 00:52:06,500
JUDY: Is that Judy crying?

562
00:52:26,300 --> 00:52:27,700
CUSTOMER: I hope I'm not too late.

563
00:52:27,700 --> 00:52:29,100
No. Come right in.

564
00:52:51,700 --> 00:52:52,700
Yeah?

565
00:52:53,300 --> 00:52:54,500
Hello, Juana.

566
00:52:54,700 --> 00:52:57,100
Yeah, he's here. Jordy, it's for you.

567
00:53:02,300 --> 00:53:03,500
Yes, dear?

568
00:53:07,700 --> 00:53:10,300
Stay right there, honey.
I'm coming right down.

569
00:53:14,700 --> 00:53:17,300
Don't you folks wait on us, we'll catch up.

570
00:53:18,700 --> 00:53:20,300
Son, you're way behind.

571
00:53:23,300 --> 00:53:25,700
Howdy, everybody, look what we found.

572
00:53:32,100 --> 00:53:33,300
There you are.

573
00:53:34,500 --> 00:53:36,100
We were getting worried.

574
00:53:36,900 --> 00:53:38,900
You'd better get dressed, Jett.

575
00:53:41,100 --> 00:53:44,100
You wanted me to go over
the speech with you, too.

576
00:53:44,700 --> 00:53:46,500
Come on, we'd better hurry.

577
00:53:48,900 --> 00:53:52,100
I'm sorry, but it happens to be
Mr. Jett Rink's orders, himself.

578
00:53:52,500 --> 00:53:54,100
I'm just working here.

579
00:53:54,300 --> 00:53:56,700
Everybody's orders. Same all over town.

580
00:53:56,900 --> 00:54:00,700
The young lady should have gone
to a place where they do her people.

581
00:54:13,700 --> 00:54:15,900
BAWLEY: If it isn't the queen herself!

582
00:54:16,500 --> 00:54:18,100
-Are you having fun?
-We're making out.

583
00:54:18,300 --> 00:54:20,100
-How are you doing?
-Good.

584
00:54:20,700 --> 00:54:22,500
Where are Mom and Dad?

585
00:54:22,700 --> 00:54:24,300
Don't trifle with your luck.

586
00:54:26,100 --> 00:54:27,100
There you are.

587
00:54:27,700 --> 00:54:29,900
You wanted to talk to me, Dad?

588
00:54:30,300 --> 00:54:33,700
If you can spare me a moment,
I'd like to talk to you, young lady.

589
00:54:33,700 --> 00:54:34,900
LUZ II: Dad, must we now?

590
00:54:35,100 --> 00:54:38,100
Jordan, we must hurry to be in time
for the grand entrance.

591
00:54:38,300 --> 00:54:40,900
<i>Luz, darling, you look just beautiful!</i>

592
00:54:41,900 --> 00:54:44,900
Help me round everybody up.
I'm sorry I'm so late.

593
00:54:45,300 --> 00:54:46,900
All right, people....

594
00:54:48,700 --> 00:54:50,300
[Resounding clap of thunder]

595
00:55:25,100 --> 00:55:27,300
Did some of you boys change this around?

596
00:55:28,500 --> 00:55:32,300
We haven't changed a single comma.
Changes tend to throw you.

597
00:55:33,100 --> 00:55:37,300
"Columbus discovered only the shell
of this country. Agassiz came...."

598
00:55:44,300 --> 00:55:45,500
Where's Rink?

599
00:55:45,700 --> 00:55:47,300
He went thataway.

600
00:55:53,900 --> 00:55:55,300
[Crowd hooting]

601
00:56:01,700 --> 00:56:04,300
Looks like I just come in for a root beer.

602
00:56:04,700 --> 00:56:07,700
<i>That, my friend, is a Texas range.</i>

603
00:56:24,500 --> 00:56:26,300
VASHTI: What're you doing
sitting up there?

604
00:56:26,300 --> 00:56:30,700
"You've heard of Paul Revere?"
The Texan said, "Paul Revere?

605
00:56:31,300 --> 00:56:34,500
"Oh, yes. Ain't he the fellow
that had to ride for help?"

606
00:56:36,500 --> 00:56:38,100
[Hooting and applause]

607
00:56:40,900 --> 00:56:44,100
<i>MC: In just a few moments,</i>
<i>Mr. Rink himself...</i>

608
00:56:44,500 --> 00:56:46,900
<i>will be here at the microphone.</i>

609
00:56:47,100 --> 00:56:48,700
Come on, let's go.

610
00:56:56,100 --> 00:56:58,500
Jordy is looking for Jett Rink.

611
00:56:58,700 --> 00:56:59,700
What?

612
00:57:07,700 --> 00:57:12,100
Where we had our hair done. Jordy wants
to fight Jett because it was his orders.

613
00:57:12,100 --> 00:57:15,100
On account of Juana. The girl said
they didn't take wetbacks.

614
00:57:24,500 --> 00:57:26,300
[Band plays lively song]

615
00:57:52,500 --> 00:57:54,100
[Crowd sings along with band]

616
00:57:59,100 --> 00:58:01,300
Stay here, honey, I'll be right back.

617
00:58:12,700 --> 00:58:14,900
You invited me here to insult my wife.

618
00:58:16,100 --> 00:58:17,700
You're gonna answer for it!

619
00:58:19,100 --> 00:58:21,300
Ain't you the one who married the squaw?

620
00:58:22,100 --> 00:58:24,300
What's the matter, boy?
Not having a good time?

621
00:58:24,300 --> 00:58:27,300
Get them up, Rink! Everybody knows
you got this coming to you!

622
00:58:27,500 --> 00:58:28,700
Jordy, no!

623
00:58:46,300 --> 00:58:50,100
You want it in front of everybody,
or you want to come outside?

624
00:58:51,300 --> 00:58:54,900
I don't care much whether it's here
or outside...

625
00:58:55,500 --> 00:58:59,300
so long as I get one punch
at that stuck-up face of yours.

626
00:59:03,100 --> 00:59:05,100
Sit down.

627
00:59:08,700 --> 00:59:09,700
Governor.

628
00:59:10,300 --> 00:59:11,900
<i>How are you this evening?</i>

629
00:59:12,900 --> 00:59:17,100
<i>MC: And now, to introduce our guest</i>
<i>of honor, we hear from a man...</i>

630
00:59:17,300 --> 00:59:21,700
<i>known from the rocky coast of Maine</i>
<i>to the Golden Gate in California.</i>

631
00:59:22,300 --> 00:59:25,100
<i>Ladies and gentlemen, our own...</i>

632
00:59:25,500 --> 00:59:27,500
<i>Senator Oliver Whiteside.</i>

633
00:59:27,500 --> 00:59:29,100
[Audience applauds]

634
00:59:34,300 --> 00:59:36,300
[Begins his speech]

635
00:59:42,500 --> 00:59:43,700
[Cat squeals]

636
00:59:53,500 --> 00:59:54,900
BICK: Get them up.

637
00:59:56,500 --> 00:59:59,100
You had this coming to you for a long time.

638
01:00:04,500 --> 01:00:06,900
You'll get what you gave my boy.

639
01:00:07,700 --> 01:00:08,700
Get them up.

640
01:00:08,900 --> 01:00:09,900
Get them up!

641
01:00:12,100 --> 01:00:14,100
WHITESIDE:
<i>...proud, friendly...</i>

642
01:00:14,500 --> 01:00:17,500
<i>warm-hearted, successful.</i>

643
01:00:18,100 --> 01:00:21,300
<i>Yes, successful I am sure....</i>

644
01:00:28,100 --> 01:00:30,100
You ain't even worth hitting.

645
01:00:34,500 --> 01:00:36,500
You want to know something true?

646
01:00:38,500 --> 01:00:39,900
You're all through.

647
01:01:01,500 --> 01:01:04,500
WHITESIDE:
<i>I'm going to ask you</i>
<i>to come with me tonight...</i>

648
01:01:04,700 --> 01:01:08,900
<i>as I turn back the pages</i>
<i>in my book of happy memories...</i>

649
01:01:09,300 --> 01:01:12,700
<i>and I recall the first time</i>
<i>I saw young Jett Rink.</i>

650
01:01:12,900 --> 01:01:15,100
BICK: Where's the boy?
LESLIE: Juana took him upstairs.

651
01:01:15,300 --> 01:01:16,500
Let's get out of here.

652
01:01:16,500 --> 01:01:17,900
LESLIE: I'll go get Luz.

653
01:01:22,300 --> 01:01:24,100
Come on, Luz. We're leaving.

654
01:01:24,900 --> 01:01:26,700
Excuse me, please.

655
01:01:30,900 --> 01:01:32,900
WHITESIDE:
<i>The years passed quickly...</i>

656
01:01:33,300 --> 01:01:35,700
<i>as the years have a way of doing.</i>

657
01:01:35,700 --> 01:01:37,300
<i>And now I see Jett Rink...</i>

658
01:01:39,100 --> 01:01:40,700
[Bottle breaks]

659
01:01:42,900 --> 01:01:47,100
<i>afraid of neither opposition nor hard work...</i>

660
01:01:47,500 --> 01:01:50,100
<i>his eyes set on the far distant...</i>

661
01:01:50,300 --> 01:01:53,500
<i>goal toward which he's ever working...</i>

662
01:01:53,900 --> 01:01:56,100
<i>planning, striving.</i>

663
01:01:59,300 --> 01:02:01,700
<i>And now we come to Jett Rink, the man.</i>

664
01:02:02,900 --> 01:02:05,300
<i>Texas has been kind to Jett Rink.</i>

665
01:02:05,900 --> 01:02:09,500
<i>And Jett, never forgetting this kindness...</i>

666
01:02:09,900 --> 01:02:12,500
<i>is ever ready to devote his resources...</i>

667
01:02:12,900 --> 01:02:16,300
<i>to the greater glory of the state</i>
<i>which reared him...</i>

668
01:02:16,500 --> 01:02:19,500
<i>which, in turn, does honor to him tonight...</i>

669
01:02:19,900 --> 01:02:23,300
<i>in this great gathering here present.</i>

670
01:02:24,900 --> 01:02:27,100
<i>And now, my friends, here...</i>

671
01:02:27,500 --> 01:02:31,900
<i>and to the thousands of you</i>
<i>listening across the nation...</i>

672
01:02:32,100 --> 01:02:33,500
<i>I have the privilege, yes...</i>

673
01:02:35,700 --> 01:02:41,100
<i>I have the great honor to introduce</i>
<i>a legend in his own time...</i>

674
01:02:41,700 --> 01:02:43,300
<i>a great Texan...</i>

675
01:02:43,700 --> 01:02:46,300
<i>an outstanding American!</i>

676
01:02:46,700 --> 01:02:49,700
<i>Yes, my friends, a man!</i>

677
01:02:50,100 --> 01:02:53,100
<i>I give to you Jett Rink!</i>

678
01:02:56,900 --> 01:02:58,900
[Band plays lively song]

679
01:03:25,900 --> 01:03:27,700
JORDAN: You can count on me.

680
01:03:31,900 --> 01:03:33,500
All right, goodbye.

681
01:03:35,300 --> 01:03:36,300
How bad?

682
01:03:36,700 --> 01:03:38,700
It hit pretty hard in Vientecito.

683
01:03:39,300 --> 01:03:43,300
Dr. Guerra set up an auxiliary hospital.
He needs help. I've got to go there.

684
01:03:43,900 --> 01:03:47,100
You'll make better time
if you wait till first light and fly.

685
01:03:47,300 --> 01:03:50,100
I hate to spend the night under Jett's roof.

686
01:03:50,300 --> 01:03:55,100
Me, too. If we weren't transporting
a circus, we'd all hightail it out of here.

687
01:03:57,500 --> 01:03:59,100
[Juana singing a lullaby]

688
01:04:10,900 --> 01:04:13,500
I hope she doesn't let this
upset her too much.

689
01:04:14,100 --> 01:04:15,900
This business tonight...

690
01:04:17,300 --> 01:04:21,500
it's just one of those things.
The best thing to do is forget about it.

691
01:04:22,500 --> 01:04:25,700
Go ahead and forget it.
Me, I'm going to remember it!

692
01:04:27,100 --> 01:04:28,700
Now look, Jordy.

693
01:04:29,500 --> 01:04:30,700
Take it easy.

694
01:04:31,700 --> 01:04:35,100
We've had just about enough excitement
around here for one night.

695
01:04:35,700 --> 01:04:37,100
Yeah, I guess so.

696
01:04:41,300 --> 01:04:44,300
You've always had a mind of your own
and used it.

697
01:04:45,100 --> 01:04:47,500
You've done things your own way.

698
01:04:51,100 --> 01:04:54,700
You knew what you were doing
when you married in that direction.

699
01:04:56,900 --> 01:05:00,700
I told you myself the morning
after you broke the news, remember?

700
01:05:02,100 --> 01:05:06,100
I told you then that I knew
Juana was a mighty fine little gal...

701
01:05:07,500 --> 01:05:10,900
but that marrying her was asking
for trouble. Remember?

702
01:05:11,300 --> 01:05:12,700
I told you that.

703
01:05:14,500 --> 01:05:18,300
Lots of folks in these parts
get pretty jumpy about that sort of thing.

704
01:05:18,300 --> 01:05:19,500
Jett's only one of them.

705
01:05:19,500 --> 01:05:23,500
I know those people. We've run
into this before. We're doing fine.

706
01:05:25,700 --> 01:05:29,300
I'm concerned it has to do with the people
that ought to know better.

707
01:05:33,300 --> 01:05:34,700
Like my own father.

708
01:05:36,900 --> 01:05:40,700
Just the simple truth. That's you.
That's the way you think.

709
01:05:41,500 --> 01:05:45,700
I don't care about Jett Rink,
but you, Papa, that's different.

710
01:05:46,300 --> 01:05:47,900
Now you look here, Jordy!

711
01:05:48,700 --> 01:05:50,500
You can't talk to me like that.

712
01:05:51,900 --> 01:05:53,500
No man can!

713
01:05:55,900 --> 01:05:59,300
I'm a fair man. I've been fair all my life,
with everybody!

714
01:06:00,100 --> 01:06:03,900
<i>And you, my own son,</i>
<i>can't tell me that I'm not a fair man!</i>

715
01:06:07,900 --> 01:06:09,100
Look, Jordy...

716
01:06:10,300 --> 01:06:13,300
there's ways of living,
and there's ways of doing things...

717
01:06:13,500 --> 01:06:16,700
that folks abide by when they want
to live right and happily...

718
01:06:16,700 --> 01:06:18,700
in the comfort of their own people.

719
01:06:19,100 --> 01:06:22,100
<i>I always say that Juana is</i>
<i>a mighty fine gal, but--</i>

720
01:06:22,100 --> 01:06:25,100
Don't sit there and prove what I say!
I don't like to hear it!

721
01:06:25,700 --> 01:06:27,500
You're not being fair!

722
01:06:29,100 --> 01:06:31,900
When that ruckus started,
who went after Rink?

723
01:06:32,300 --> 01:06:34,100
Your old man.

724
01:06:34,300 --> 01:06:37,100
-Who took him to account? Your old man.
-And why?

725
01:06:38,100 --> 01:06:39,100
Because of my wife?

726
01:06:39,300 --> 01:06:40,300
-Yes!
-No!

727
01:06:40,700 --> 01:06:43,300
Because your son, Jordan Benedict...

728
01:06:43,300 --> 01:06:46,300
descendant of the long, proud line
of Reata...

729
01:06:46,500 --> 01:06:50,300
got knocked flat on his back
in front of all of Texas. That's why!

730
01:07:06,900 --> 01:07:09,500
Forget it. Don't worry yourself about it.

731
01:07:18,300 --> 01:07:22,900
<i>Mom, you made a mistake when you got</i>
<i>yourself mixed up with us rowdy Texans.</i>

732
01:07:24,300 --> 01:07:28,700
LUZ II: I'm shocked at you! I'm shocked
at all of us! I'm just so ashamed!

733
01:07:29,300 --> 01:07:33,500
I'll never forget the sight of my brother
barging into the grand ballroom...

734
01:07:33,500 --> 01:07:37,900
with all of our friends, disgracing us!
Then my father made it a bigger brawl!

735
01:07:37,900 --> 01:07:40,300
How can I face people again?

736
01:07:40,300 --> 01:07:42,700
JORDAN: Keep seeing Jett and
you won't have to face me.

737
01:07:42,700 --> 01:07:43,700
LESLIE: Children!

738
01:07:44,100 --> 01:07:46,100
How about that anyway, Mom?

739
01:07:46,100 --> 01:07:47,900
LESLIE: I haven't been asked.

740
01:07:47,900 --> 01:07:51,300
It seems that my family
just can't tolerate his success.

741
01:07:51,500 --> 01:07:52,900
My darling, Luz.

742
01:07:52,900 --> 01:07:56,100
LUZ II: Tonight meant a lot to Jett.
Really. I know.

743
01:07:57,500 --> 01:08:01,100
If I only knew how to apologize to him,
I'd go to him now.

744
01:08:02,900 --> 01:08:05,300
<i>But I can't face all those people.</i>

745
01:08:06,100 --> 01:08:08,300
The party is over. They've all gone home.

746
01:08:09,700 --> 01:08:12,300
He passed out like a light
in front of the whole crowd.

747
01:08:12,500 --> 01:08:13,500
Oh, no!

748
01:08:13,900 --> 01:08:15,700
That's what we heard, Luz.

749
01:08:17,300 --> 01:08:19,500
He must have been ill.

750
01:08:20,300 --> 01:08:22,100
Weak with shame or something.

751
01:08:22,500 --> 01:08:25,100
He was plain drunk, if you'll forgive me.

752
01:08:26,300 --> 01:08:27,900
I don't believe you.

753
01:08:29,500 --> 01:08:32,700
The party broke up early,
but not a minute too soon.

754
01:08:39,100 --> 01:08:41,100
Give me Mr. Rink's penthouse, please.

755
01:08:41,300 --> 01:08:44,700
You're not going up there,
even if I have to sit on you!

756
01:08:45,900 --> 01:08:48,500
It's important. Do you know where he is?

757
01:08:48,700 --> 01:08:51,500
Luz, it's not like you
to make a fool of yourself.

758
01:08:52,900 --> 01:08:56,300
I know where he is, honey.
Come along with Uncle Bawley.

759
01:08:58,500 --> 01:09:00,900
LESLIE: All right, Luz. If you must go.

760
01:09:03,100 --> 01:09:04,300
I must.

761
01:09:06,500 --> 01:09:09,700
I've always held a strange power
over your mother.

762
01:09:16,900 --> 01:09:18,500
I'm sorry, Mother.

763
01:09:29,300 --> 01:09:33,100
What do you say, doll face?
About ready to come along with me?

764
01:09:35,900 --> 01:09:37,300
It's time we hit the hay.

765
01:09:37,500 --> 01:09:39,300
[Jett drunkenly babbles]

766
01:09:42,700 --> 01:09:43,700
I give up.

767
01:09:48,700 --> 01:09:49,900
Can we go to work now?

768
01:09:49,900 --> 01:09:53,300
Leave him alone.
He owns the place, let him enjoy it.

769
01:09:53,500 --> 01:09:54,500
JETT: Shut up.

770
01:09:55,500 --> 01:09:56,700
<i>Shut up!</i>

771
01:10:14,700 --> 01:10:17,700
Ladies and gentlemen
and distinguished guests.

772
01:10:21,500 --> 01:10:24,100
<i>I just want to count the blessings...</i>

773
01:10:26,100 --> 01:10:29,700
that this great domain
has bestowed upon her humble son.

774
01:10:32,100 --> 01:10:33,300
My friends...

775
01:10:35,900 --> 01:10:37,900
this is a man.

776
01:10:44,500 --> 01:10:46,100
Old Mother Texas!

777
01:10:47,900 --> 01:10:49,900
What did she give to me?

778
01:10:50,500 --> 01:10:52,900
<i>Not a goddamn thing.</i>

779
01:10:53,500 --> 01:10:57,100
<i>You've got to work and sweat</i>
<i>and steal it from her.</i>

780
01:10:59,700 --> 01:11:04,300
<i>But I got mine right out of the ground.</i>

781
01:11:07,300 --> 01:11:08,700
Poor Jett...

782
01:11:11,300 --> 01:11:13,300
fighting for what's good.

783
01:11:13,900 --> 01:11:15,100
Flunky!

784
01:11:16,500 --> 01:11:18,900
Flunky for Bick Benedict...

785
01:11:20,300 --> 01:11:21,500
her husband.

786
01:11:25,900 --> 01:11:27,300
Poor Jett!

787
01:11:34,300 --> 01:11:36,100
Poor pretty Leslie!

788
01:11:38,100 --> 01:11:39,300
Pretty Leslie....

789
01:11:41,500 --> 01:11:45,700
<i>Pretty Leslie.</i>
<i>Wonderful, beautiful girl bride!</i>

790
01:11:48,100 --> 01:11:49,500
<i>Poor boy.</i>

791
01:11:50,500 --> 01:11:51,500
<i>Rich....</i>

792
01:11:52,100 --> 01:11:53,700
<i>Rich Mrs. Benedict.</i>

793
01:11:57,500 --> 01:11:59,100
<i>She's beautiful.</i>

794
01:12:00,500 --> 01:12:01,700
<i>Lovely.</i>

795
01:12:02,500 --> 01:12:04,100
<i>The woman a man wants.</i>

796
01:12:05,100 --> 01:12:07,500
<i>A woman a man has got to have, too!</i>

797
01:12:13,100 --> 01:12:15,500
[Melancholy instrumental music]

798
01:12:30,300 --> 01:12:32,300
LUZ II: Thank you, Uncle Bawley.

799
01:12:34,900 --> 01:12:36,100
Governor...

800
01:12:40,100 --> 01:12:42,100
you know what you can do?

801
01:12:56,500 --> 01:12:58,500
[Family singing to popular 1940s song]

802
01:13:13,500 --> 01:13:15,500
[Bick honks horn]

803
01:13:18,500 --> 01:13:20,500
As soon as it lands, I'll sell it.

804
01:13:20,900 --> 01:13:21,500
Good.

805
01:13:21,500 --> 01:13:22,700
This is for me, boy.

806
01:13:22,700 --> 01:13:23,900
<i>The simple life.</i>

807
01:13:24,100 --> 01:13:26,100
<i>No more of this highflying nonsense.</i>

808
01:13:47,700 --> 01:13:49,100
[Honks horn]

809
01:13:55,300 --> 01:13:58,300
Juana, how does a hamburger
and a piece of pie sound to you?

810
01:13:58,500 --> 01:13:59,500
Sounds very good.

811
01:14:00,700 --> 01:14:02,900
No more of this highfalutin stuff.

812
01:14:03,100 --> 01:14:05,700
Let's stop at this drive-in
and have us some chicken.

813
01:14:05,700 --> 01:14:07,500
<i>Then we can eat it with our fingers.</i>

814
01:14:09,100 --> 01:14:11,100
[Military band song]

815
01:14:57,100 --> 01:15:00,900
Nice place you have here. I've been
intending to stop every time I drove by.

816
01:15:00,900 --> 01:15:02,100
Thank you.

817
01:15:02,100 --> 01:15:04,500
What do you recommend?
How is the fried chicken?

818
01:15:04,700 --> 01:15:07,100
Little Jordy wants ice cream, Grandpa.

819
01:15:08,700 --> 01:15:09,700
Grandpa?

820
01:15:11,500 --> 01:15:13,300
Ice cream it shall be.

821
01:15:14,500 --> 01:15:16,500
<i>Give the little fellow some ice cream.</i>

822
01:15:16,700 --> 01:15:18,300
SARGE: Ice cream?

823
01:15:18,300 --> 01:15:20,700
I thought that kid would want a tamale.

824
01:15:31,300 --> 01:15:33,300
Give them what they want.

825
01:15:49,300 --> 01:15:51,500
What do you say? Is this all right?

826
01:15:52,300 --> 01:15:53,700
It's good.

827
01:15:54,900 --> 01:15:57,500
BICK: After all that fancy food
and high living.

828
01:15:57,700 --> 01:15:59,100
This is the life.

829
01:16:15,500 --> 01:16:16,700
SARGE: Hey, you.

830
01:16:19,900 --> 01:16:23,300
The plane should arrive in Benedict
around 1:30.

831
01:16:27,300 --> 01:16:29,100
You're in the wrong place.

832
01:16:29,300 --> 01:16:31,500
Come on, let's get out of here.

833
01:16:33,100 --> 01:16:34,900
Your money is no good here.

834
01:16:36,300 --> 01:16:37,900
Come on, let's go.

835
01:16:39,700 --> 01:16:40,700
You, too.

836
01:16:40,700 --> 01:16:42,100
BICK: Hold on a minute.

837
01:16:49,300 --> 01:16:51,100
SARGE: Yes, what do you want?

838
01:16:52,900 --> 01:16:57,700
Look here, Sarge. I'd sure appreciate it
if you were more polite to these people.

839
01:16:58,900 --> 01:17:00,300
SARGE: You would, eh?

840
01:17:01,300 --> 01:17:04,300
I'm Bick Benedict.
Your neighbor, you might say.

841
01:17:04,900 --> 01:17:07,500
SARGE: Does that give you
special privileges?

842
01:17:07,900 --> 01:17:12,100
The name Benedict's meant something
to people around here for a long time.

843
01:17:14,500 --> 01:17:16,700
That there papoose down there...

844
01:17:17,700 --> 01:17:19,300
is his name Benedict, too?

845
01:17:26,900 --> 01:17:29,900
Yes. Come to think of it, it is.

846
01:17:32,300 --> 01:17:33,900
SARGE: Forget I asked you.

847
01:17:34,300 --> 01:17:37,300
<i>Go sit down,</i>
<i>and we ain't gonna have no trouble.</i>

848
01:17:37,700 --> 01:17:40,300
But this bunch's gonna eat
somewhere else.

849
01:17:41,500 --> 01:17:43,100
All right, come on. Let's go.

850
01:17:43,100 --> 01:17:44,500
Come on, you, too.

851
01:17:48,500 --> 01:17:50,500
You're out of line, mister.

852
01:17:54,900 --> 01:17:56,700
[Sound of punches being struck]

853
01:17:57,100 --> 01:17:59,100
[Military band song starts again]

854
01:20:03,700 --> 01:20:05,700
[Organ music playing]

855
01:20:08,500 --> 01:20:11,300
Is that the best that old horse thief can do?

856
01:20:12,100 --> 01:20:15,300
He's feeling your mood, darling.

857
01:20:16,500 --> 01:20:19,500
There's a lot of
<i>Clair de Lune</i>
in both of you old fire-eaters.

858
01:20:20,500 --> 01:20:22,700
You're both rather gentle creatures.

859
01:20:23,100 --> 01:20:24,300
How awful!

860
01:20:28,300 --> 01:20:29,700
Those kids....

861
01:20:30,300 --> 01:20:31,700
<i>Look at them.</i>

862
01:20:32,300 --> 01:20:35,500
<i>Those kids, in their infinite wisdom,</i>
<i>are smarter than we are.</i>

863
01:20:36,500 --> 01:20:39,300
They know I'm a disgrace.
And they don't hesitate to say so.

864
01:20:39,700 --> 01:20:41,100
[Mooing]

865
01:20:41,500 --> 01:20:43,700
Even the calf's got my number.

866
01:20:44,500 --> 01:20:45,700
[Baaing]

867
01:20:45,900 --> 01:20:48,500
I don't have to take it from a sheep!

868
01:20:49,900 --> 01:20:51,300
LESLIE: Now, Jordan!

869
01:20:51,500 --> 01:20:52,500
[Telephone rings]

870
01:20:57,900 --> 01:21:01,700
Hello, Vashti. We're all fine.
How'd you make it back?

871
01:21:04,700 --> 01:21:07,300
-They all made it back in one piece.
-Jolly.

872
01:21:08,100 --> 01:21:11,500
Yes, all our guests have finally gone.
Thank goodness!

873
01:21:14,100 --> 01:21:16,700
But more have left than we bargained for.

874
01:21:16,900 --> 01:21:20,700
Luz has gone on to Hollywood with Lola,
whatever the name was.

875
01:21:22,900 --> 01:21:26,100
She decided she would like to see
how she liked Hollywood.

876
01:21:28,300 --> 01:21:29,900
We never had one in the family.

877
01:21:30,100 --> 01:21:31,700
Good Lord, an actress!

878
01:21:34,100 --> 01:21:38,300
All you can do is raise them.
You can't live their lives for them.

879
01:21:41,100 --> 01:21:43,700
Judy and Bob are out looking at a ranch.

880
01:21:44,300 --> 01:21:45,500
A small one.

881
01:21:47,700 --> 01:21:50,500
<i>Jordy and Juana are gonna move</i>
<i>into Vientecito.</i>

882
01:21:50,700 --> 01:21:53,700
<i>And we, we're home minding the babies.</i>

883
01:21:58,500 --> 01:22:02,700
BAWLEY: The sun's going down.
When are you going to open up the bar?

884
01:22:02,700 --> 01:22:04,300
Anytime. Go ahead.

885
01:22:05,500 --> 01:22:08,300
Remember, one of these days
that bourbon's gonna kill you.

886
01:22:08,300 --> 01:22:10,500
Okay. lt'll be me or it.

887
01:22:11,100 --> 01:22:12,700
One of us has got to go.

888
01:22:15,100 --> 01:22:18,700
I'm going to stay right here.
It's coming onto spring.

889
01:22:19,700 --> 01:22:22,700
Roundup time is no time
to be away from Reata.

890
01:22:32,100 --> 01:22:35,900
BICK: Honey, everybody's on the move.
The strays are leaving the herd.

891
01:22:38,300 --> 01:22:43,300
I wouldn't mind it too much if you wanted
to pack up and go back home for a spell.

892
01:22:44,900 --> 01:22:45,900
Home?

893
01:22:47,100 --> 01:22:51,300
Where do you think I've been
this last breathless quarter of a century?

894
01:22:52,500 --> 01:22:53,700
Home.

895
01:22:54,300 --> 01:22:56,300
Look, boy, I belong here!

896
01:22:59,100 --> 01:23:02,100
You really want to know
what's gotten my goat?

897
01:23:04,300 --> 01:23:06,900
My own grandson doesn't even look
like one of us.

898
01:23:07,300 --> 01:23:09,900
He really looks like a little wetback.

899
01:23:15,500 --> 01:23:17,900
Little <i>muchacho</i> fires up, don't he?

900
01:23:19,500 --> 01:23:21,500
I'm sorry, Jordan Benedict IV.

901
01:23:22,300 --> 01:23:24,500
<i>There's times when a man</i>
<i>just has to be honest.</i>

902
01:23:27,900 --> 01:23:29,500
You know something, Leslie?

903
01:23:30,700 --> 01:23:32,300
There's no use kidding.

904
01:23:33,500 --> 01:23:34,900
I'm a failure.

905
01:23:35,700 --> 01:23:38,700
Nothing has turned out like I had planned.

906
01:23:42,300 --> 01:23:45,500
I just feel like my saddle's turning
right out from under me.

907
01:23:48,300 --> 01:23:50,100
Do you want to know something?

908
01:23:52,300 --> 01:23:54,100
I think you're great!

909
01:23:56,700 --> 01:24:00,100
Don't ask me why.
Some things are difficult to explain.

910
01:24:01,500 --> 01:24:05,700
You know all that fine riding
you used to do, and all that fancy roping...

911
01:24:05,700 --> 01:24:08,700
and all that glamour stuff
you did to dazzle me?

912
01:24:08,900 --> 01:24:10,300
It was impressive.

913
01:24:11,700 --> 01:24:15,100
But none of it ever made you
quite as big a man to me...

914
01:24:15,700 --> 01:24:18,900
as you were on the floor
of Sarge's hamburger joint.

915
01:24:23,100 --> 01:24:25,100
When you tumbled rearward...

916
01:24:25,300 --> 01:24:28,500
and landed crashing
into that pile of dirty dishes...

917
01:24:29,900 --> 01:24:32,100
you were at last my hero.

918
01:24:33,500 --> 01:24:35,900
That's what you always wanted to be.

919
01:24:36,500 --> 01:24:37,500
Could be.

920
01:24:38,300 --> 01:24:41,700
LESLIE: When we went into that place,
before the fight started....

921
01:24:43,700 --> 01:24:46,300
What a fight! It was glorious!

922
01:24:47,900 --> 01:24:51,300
Before we went in,
I was feeling like you are now.

923
01:24:52,300 --> 01:24:53,900
I was thinking to myself:

924
01:24:54,500 --> 01:24:55,700
"Well...

925
01:24:55,700 --> 01:24:59,300
"Jordan and l, and the others behind us,
have been failures."

926
01:25:00,700 --> 01:25:02,300
And then it happened.

927
01:25:03,300 --> 01:25:07,500
You wound up on the floor, on your back,
in the middle of the salad.

928
01:25:09,100 --> 01:25:10,500
And I said to myself:

929
01:25:11,500 --> 01:25:12,500
"Well...

930
01:25:13,300 --> 01:25:15,300
"after 100 years...

931
01:25:16,300 --> 01:25:18,100
"the Benedict family...

932
01:25:18,300 --> 01:25:20,900
"is a real big success."

933
01:25:23,500 --> 01:25:25,500
BICK: You want to know something, Leslie?

934
01:25:26,900 --> 01:25:28,900
If I live to be 90...

935
01:25:30,700 --> 01:25:33,500
I'll never be able to figure you out.

936
01:25:33,500 --> 01:25:35,100
[Lullaby playing]

937
01:25:54,500 --> 01:25:56,500
[Lively band song plays]